{
  "answer": "**In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Tujh ko duzdida nigahi yeh sikha di kis ne\" from *Bang-E-Dara Part 2* (Chapter 26), the speaker rhetorically asks a kitten (the \"beloved,\" addressed as \"you\" with \"eyes of azure blue,\" batting paws, and lap-sitting habits) who taught it \"this art of the stolen glance.\"**[^1]\n\n**The poem does not name a specific teacher. Instead, it concludes that no instruction was needed: the sense of Beauty (and Love) is innate, not exclusive to humans but present \"deep in all things,\" throbbing in every atom as a universal force.**[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Tujh ko duzdida nigahi yeh sikha di kis ne\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/26-tujh-ko-duzdida-nigahi-yeh-sikha-di-kis-ne/translation/#p-4ab922).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Tujh ko duzdida nigahi yeh sikha di kis ne\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/26-tujh-ko-duzdida-nigahi-yeh-sikha-di-kis-ne/translation/#p-69ebd5).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Tujh ko duzdida nigahi yeh sikha di kis ne\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/26-tujh-ko-duzdida-nigahi-yeh-sikha-di-kis-ne/translation/#p-a7275e).",
